comment.body:
Overall looks good but I want to kick the tyres on it a bit. 

Some minor comments as I've looked closer (I can't remember which parts I wrote but fully open to change my mind on good ways of doing things).

- Anyways, love it or hate it, you can store reactions are molecules (and convert back and forth) so *technically* you could iterate over molecules. But you probably want to keep it as IReaction as you have properties on the molecule IIRC (e.g. titles)?
- As noted in Egon's review/comment chain, the error handling is always tricky, I think I now favour the OPSIN like approach where you set some status on a return type, or even better on the thing you pass in (I can give an example).
- I think some parts like the property processing we can centralize - I think the V2000/V3000 might share/reuse the function but there is a duplicate in the SDFReader. Good opportunity to unify these.
Ah I miss-read Egon's input on the IO listener... personally I would prefer a return status on the record. So then the you force the user to decide what to do with them.

issue.title: V3K molfile: Error while parsing index atom X in bond
issue.body:
Given the following V3K molfile:

```

  Mrv2219 11302223302D          

  0  0  0     0  0            999 V3000
M  V30 BEGIN CTAB
M  V30 COUNTS 2 1 0 0 0
M  V30 BEGIN ATOM
M  V30 1 C -6.458 3.4367 0 0
M  V30 22 C -7.7917 2.6667 0 0
M  V30 END ATOM
M  V30 BEGIN BOND
M  V30 1 1 1 22
M  V30 END BOND
M  V30 END CTAB
M  END
```

I get the following error: "Error while parsing index atom 2 in bond".

AFAICT, the molfile is valid. Replacing atom index 22 in the atom and bond blocks resolves the error.

Here's the stack trace:

```
org.openscience.cdk.io.MDLV3000Reader ERROR: Error while parsing index atom 2 in bond

comment.body:
It's been on my list to rewrite the V3000 IO at some point, or rather V2000+V3000 since currently you need to know if you ``.mol`` input is V2000/V3000 before you parse it, which isn't ideal. In general the V3000 reader is not very robust and supports only a subset (bare minimum) of the format, I've added bits over the years but ultimately it needs a rewrite.

In this case the V3000 currently presumes the atom indexes are sequential, indeed all programatically generated content will be sequential. However leave this open since it's a simple fix.

Sure you've tested already but Marvin rejects it:
https://marvinjs-demo.chemaxon.com/latest/

And ChemDraw:
https://chemdrawdirect.perkinelmer.cloud/js/sample/index.html

As expected BIOVIA accepts it:
```
SQL> select smiles(mol('
  Mrv2219 11302223302D          

  0  0  0     0  0            999 V3000
M  V30 BEGIN CTAB
M  V30 COUNTS 2 1 0 0 0
M  V30 BEGIN ATOM
M  V30 1 C -6.458 3.4367 0 0
M  V30 22 C -7.7917 2.6667 0 0
M  V30 END ATOM
M  V30 BEGIN BOND
M  V30 1 1 1 22
M  V30 END BOND
M  V30 END CTAB
M  END')) from dual;
CC
```

You should get a BIOVIA draw license Rich, not expensive for a single user (much cheaper than ChemDraw for example).

comment.body:
@rapodaca did you have an old build laying around, just tested on:

```
[john@sentinel:cdk]% java -version
openjdk version "18.0.2.1" 2022-08-18
OpenJDK Runtime Environment (build 18.0.2.1+1-1)
OpenJDK 64-Bit Server VM (build 18.0.2.1+1-1, mixed mode, sharing)
[john@sentinel:cdk]%
```

And no issues with a "clean install":

```
$ mvn clean install -q -o -DskipTests  113.83s user 12.62s system 175% cpu 1:12.07 total
```

I wish this was better advertised by the JDK 18/19 are sort of like public betas and you're better using the LTS Java 8/11/17. Java 17 for example runs the build in only 20s.

```
[john@sentinel:cdk]% java -version
openjdk version "17.0.1" 2021-10-19
OpenJDK Runtime Environment (build 17.0.1+12-39)
OpenJDK 64-Bit Server VM (build 17.0.1+12-39, mixed mode, sharing)

$ mvn clean install -q -o -DskipTests  58.75s user 4.15s system 296% cpu 21.218 total
```

Hi Uli,

I'll find time to look closer but some easy fixes:
 - the build if failing due a missing file it looks likey just forgot to check something in?
 - Missing copyright header/license on the java files

pull_request.title: Query bond funcs
pull_request.body:
At some point these went out of sync with the main AtomContainer, the order.numeric() should be compared and not the ordinal() since "unset" has the largest enum in the ordinal. We also make this function null safe since it's highly likely Query molecules have unset bond order.

issue.title: Cleaner InChI mass interaction/API quality of life
issue.body:
Since InChI stores mass as a delta you need to know what the base line it is a delta from. The InChI API (and by extension JNA InChI) is asymmetric in that you pass in an exact mass and get a "isotopic shift" out - the caller then needs to translate this to something sane. I think perhaps it accepts both an exact 'mass number' or a 'isotopic shift' on input so it's not quite asymmetric but I believe it always gives an 'isotopic shift' on output.

I've just fixed the issue in CDK and found the table in the INCHI-BASE directory:
https://github.com/cdk/cdk/pull/936. It would also be possible to derive the table by round-tripping in enough values.

I wonder if doing the translation in JNA InChI would be reasonable and a more usable API?

issue.title: NPE in getInChIToStructure for radioactive elements
issue.body:
The following line throws a NullPointerException for radioactive elements like Technetium-99:
https://github.com/cdk/cdk/blob/cdk-2.8/storage/inchi/src/main/java/org/openscience/cdk/inchi/InChIToStructure.java#L195

Seems like this corresponds to `getMajorIsotope` returning null.

For example:
```java
InChIGeneratorFactory.getInstance().getInChIToStructure(
    "InChI=1S/Tc/i1+1",
    DefaultChemObjectBuilder.getInstance(),
).getAtomContainer()
```

I think the desired behavior would be to either (a) translate the NPE into a more informative CDKException, or (b) if possible, avoid the NPE altogether and continue generating the atom container.

comment.body:
Here is the mass table:
https://github.com/metamolecular/inchi/blob/0fc7adc58d4ff1c481b26e0de53cc8a404c3d381/INCHI_BASE/src/util.c

(Official code is "source available" Richard has rehosted so easy to link here)

OK I'm amazed that went unnoticed for so long. Basically an obvious omission in the BFS/shortest-path finding code, or rather a specialisation of it which takes a permutation of the vertices and only gives you paths that are lexicographically descending. Some bonkers PhD student wrote this years ago (me) and I had to relearn what was going on.

issue.title: Flipped stereochemistry for Glucose using `InChiToStructure`
issue.body:
I am parsing this InChI:
```
InChI=1S/C6H12O6/c7-1-2-3(8)4(9)5(10)6(11)12-2/h2-11H,1H2/t2-,3-,4+,5-,6+/m1/s1
```
and producing an image with `DepictionGenerator`.
I expect an image like:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/26444312/202723071-93bd5376-ac04-4dd4-940a-5efc7699abf6.png)

But this is the image that CDK is generating:
![inchi](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/26444312/202723140-6bd78a6d-fa3e-4859-836b-9e2bdc93f173.svg)

Note that I am expecting [L-Glucose](https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/L-Glucose#section=2D-Structure) but the image produced is of [D-Glucose](https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/D-Glucose).

The code I am using is essentially [this](https://github.com/ipb-halle/cdk-inchi-to-svg/blob/master/cdk-inchi-to-svg/src/main/java/de/ipb_halle/msbi/cdk_inchi_to_svg/App.java):

```clojure
(defn use-inchi [inchi]
  (let [cob (DefaultChemObjectBuilder/getInstance)
        genf (InChIGeneratorFactory/getInstance)
        parse (.getInChIToStructure genf inchi cob)
        ret (.getReturnStatus parse)
        warning (if (= ret INCHI_RET/WARNING)
                  (.getMessage parse)
                  nil)
        mol (.getAtomContainer parse)
        dg (.depict (DepictionGenerator.) mol)]
    (if warning
      (println warning)
      (do
        (.writeTo dg "inchi.svg")
        (println "Success")))))

(use-inchi "InChI=1S/C6H12O6/c7-1-2-3(8)4(9)5(10)6(11)12-2/h2-11H,1H2/t2-,3-,4+,5-,6+/m1/s1")
=> Success
```

Environment:
```
$ java --version
openjdk 17.0.5 2022-10-18
OpenJDK Runtime Environment (build 17.0.5+8-Debian-2)
OpenJDK 64-Bit Server VM (build 17.0.5+8-Debian-2, mixed mode, sharing)
```

* CDK 2.8 from maven
* `net.sf.jni-inchi` 0.8 from maven

(defn use-inchi [inchi]

        mol (.getAtomContainer parse)

comment.body:
Sorry last message got screwed up by email.

Ah you need to bootstrap it I think. 

The old javadoc could pickup run time dependency but that didn’t seem to work anymore (maybe extra module flags needed?) so you need to do the following:
- compile your code (main project)
- make cdk build utils depend on the new build
- rebuild the cdk-build-utils
- run javadoc:aggregate on the main project

Since we don’t really add many taglets it’s not normally such a pain although this is one of the reasons I would favour just in-lining the values as plain HTML.

> Personally, I consider javadocs as quite important and I struggle to validate them if I add/modify anything.

Preaching to the choir, I’m not the one you need to convince. #908

comment.body:
It looks like it's just a skipped attribute in the CML input. @egonw is the CML wizard who will be able to confirm if there is some special semantics being missed or not. Based on what the descriptor is doing and the test cases I don't think there is anything wrong.

https://github.com/cdk/cdk/blob/main/storage/pdb/src/main/resources/org/openscience/cdk/templates/data/list_aminoacids.cml#L2

```xml
<list title="List of amino acids" convention="cdk:substructureList"
        xmlns="http://www.xml-cml.org/schema"
        xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
    
```

comment.body:
How are you accessing this? I don’t provide any of those API points.

Mainly curious.

The web API (I have not idea what api you are using) expects a SMARTS and not a SMILES. There is a subtle difference but you’ve queried for a nitrogen with a hydrogen attached but there are none.

“c1ncnc1”
Or
“c1nc[nX3]c1”

Yes it uses secrets, however since the branch is in your fork it will not see the secret. So o thought the work around was you define a secret in an environment then it can be seen if the workflow gets approved to run - but that didn’t work

Oh grrr... not finished yet but can see it still didn't pickup the SonarCloud token. This is infuriating, we could just expose the token publicly but I thought how I had set this up was a good option. i.e. me/egon need to click run on the PR
Could you rebase on master @uli-f, I think have configure SonarCloud so we can run it now.

comment.body:
Overall looks good but I want to kick the tyres on it a bit. 

Some minor comments as I've looked closer (I can't remember which parts I wrote but fully open to change my mind on good ways of doing things).

- Anyways, love it or hate it, you can store reactions are molecules (and convert back and forth) so *technically* you could iterate over molecules. But you probably want to keep it as IReaction as you have properties on the molecule IIRC (e.g. titles)?
- As noted in Egon's review/comment chain, the error handling is always tricky, I think I now favour the OPSIN like approach where you set some status on a return type, or even better on the thing you pass in (I can give an example).
- I think some parts like the property processing we can centralize - I think the V2000/V3000 might share/reuse the function but there is a duplicate in the SDFReader. Good opportunity to unify these.
Ah I miss-read Egon's input on the IO listener... personally I would prefer a return status on the record. So then the you force the user to decide what to do with them.

issue.title: V3K molfile: Error while parsing index atom X in bond
issue.body:
Given the following V3K molfile:

```

  Mrv2219 11302223302D          

  0  0  0     0  0            999 V3000
M  V30 BEGIN CTAB
M  V30 COUNTS 2 1 0 0 0
M  V30 BEGIN ATOM
M  V30 1 C -6.458 3.4367 0 0
M  V30 22 C -7.7917 2.6667 0 0
M  V30 END ATOM
M  V30 BEGIN BOND
M  V30 1 1 1 22
M  V30 END BOND
M  V30 END CTAB
M  END
```

I get the following error: "Error while parsing index atom 2 in bond".

AFAICT, the molfile is valid. Replacing atom index 22 in the atom and bond blocks resolves the error.

Here's the stack trace:

comment.body:
It's been on my list to rewrite the V3000 IO at some point, or rather V2000+V3000 since currently you need to know if you ``.mol`` input is V2000/V3000 before you parse it, which isn't ideal. In general the V3000 reader is not very robust and supports only a subset (bare minimum) of the format, I've added bits over the years but ultimately it needs a rewrite.

In this case the V3000 currently presumes the atom indexes are sequential, indeed all programatically generated content will be sequential. However leave this open since it's a simple fix.

Sure you've tested already but Marvin rejects it:
https://marvinjs-demo.chemaxon.com/latest/

And ChemDraw:
https://chemdrawdirect.perkinelmer.cloud/js/sample/index.html

As expected BIOVIA accepts it:
```
SQL> select smiles(mol('
  Mrv2219 11302223302D          

  0  0  0     0  0            999 V3000
M  V30 BEGIN CTAB
M  V30 COUNTS 2 1 0 0 0
M  V30 BEGIN ATOM
M  V30 1 C -6.458 3.4367 0 0
M  V30 22 C -7.7917 2.6667 0 0
M  V30 END ATOM
M  V30 BEGIN BOND
M  V30 1 1 1 22
M  V30 END BOND
M  V30 END CTAB
M  END')) from dual;
CC
```

You should get a BIOVIA draw license Rich, not expensive for a single user (much cheaper than ChemDraw for example).

I'm trying to compile the current master (45bb1a) as per the README (`mvn install`). The system is MacOS Monterrey (M1).

comment.body:
@rapodaca did you have an old build laying around, just tested on:

```
[john@sentinel:cdk]% java -version
openjdk version "18.0.2.1" 2022-08-18
OpenJDK Runtime Environment (build 18.0.2.1+1-1)
OpenJDK 64-Bit Server VM (build 18.0.2.1+1-1, mixed mode, sharing)
[john@sentinel:cdk]%
```

And no issues with a "clean install":

```
$ mvn clean install -q -o -DskipTests  113.83s user 12.62s system 175% cpu 1:12.07 total
```

I wish this was better advertised by the JDK 18/19 are sort of like public betas and you're better using the LTS Java 8/11/17. Java 17 for example runs the build in only 20s.

```
[john@sentinel:cdk]% java -version
openjdk version "17.0.1" 2021-10-19
OpenJDK Runtime Environment (build 17.0.1+12-39)
OpenJDK 64-Bit Server VM (build 17.0.1+12-39, mixed mode, sharing)

$ mvn clean install -q -o -DskipTests  58.75s user 4.15s system 296% cpu 21.218 total
```

Hi Uli,

I'll find time to look closer but some easy fixes:
 - the build if failing due a missing file it looks likey just forgot to check something in?
 - Missing copyright header/license on the java files

issue.title: Cleaner InChI mass interaction/API quality of life
issue.body:
Since InChI stores mass as a delta you need to know what the base line it is a delta from. The InChI API (and by extension JNA InChI) is asymmetric in that you pass in an exact mass and get a "isotopic shift" out - the caller then needs to translate this to something sane. I think perhaps it accepts both an exact 'mass number' or a 'isotopic shift' on input so it's not quite asymmetric but I believe it always gives an 'isotopic shift' on output.

I've just fixed the issue in CDK and found the table in the INCHI-BASE directory:
https://github.com/cdk/cdk/pull/936. It would also be possible to derive the table by round-tripping in enough values.

I wonder if doing the translation in JNA InChI would be reasonable and a more usable API?

issue.title: NPE in getInChIToStructure for radioactive elements
issue.body:
The following line throws a NullPointerException for radioactive elements like Technetium-99:
https://github.com/cdk/cdk/blob/cdk-2.8/storage/inchi/src/main/java/org/openscience/cdk/inchi/InChIToStructure.java#L195

Seems like this corresponds to `getMajorIsotope` returning null.

For example:
```java
InChIGeneratorFactory.getInstance().getInChIToStructure(
    "InChI=1S/Tc/i1+1",
    DefaultChemObjectBuilder.getInstance(),
).getAtomContainer()
```

I think the desired behavior would be to either (a) translate the NPE into a more informative CDKException, or (b) if possible, avoid the NPE altogether and continue generating the atom container.

comment.body:
Here is the mass table:
https://github.com/metamolecular/inchi/blob/0fc7adc58d4ff1c481b26e0de53cc8a404c3d381/INCHI_BASE/src/util.c

(Official code is "source available" Richard has rehosted so easy to link here)

OK I'm amazed that went unnoticed for so long. Basically an obvious omission in the BFS/shortest-path finding code, or rather a specialisation of it which takes a permutation of the vertices and only gives you paths that are lexicographically descending. Some bonkers PhD student wrote this years ago (me) and I had to relearn what was going on.

issue.title: Flipped stereochemistry for Glucose using `InChiToStructure`
issue.body:
I am parsing this InChI:
```
InChI=1S/C6H12O6/c7-1-2-3(8)4(9)5(10)6(11)12-2/h2-11H,1H2/t2-,3-,4+,5-,6+/m1/s1
```
and producing an image with `DepictionGenerator`.
I expect an image like:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/26444312/202723071-93bd5376-ac04-4dd4-940a-5efc7699abf6.png)

But this is the image that CDK is generating:
![inchi](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/26444312/202723140-6bd78a6d-fa3e-4859-836b-9e2bdc93f173.svg)

Note that I am expecting [L-Glucose](https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/L-Glucose#section=2D-Structure) but the image produced is of [D-Glucose](https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/D-Glucose).

The code I am using is essentially [this](https://github.com/ipb-halle/cdk-inchi-to-svg/blob/master/cdk-inchi-to-svg/src/main/java/de/ipb_halle/msbi/cdk_inchi_to_svg/App.java):

```clojure
(defn use-inchi [inchi]
  (let [cob (DefaultChemObjectBuilder/getInstance)
        genf (InChIGeneratorFactory/getInstance)
        parse (.getInChIToStructure genf inchi cob)
        ret (.getReturnStatus parse)
        warning (if (= ret INCHI_RET/WARNING)
                  (.getMessage parse)
                  nil)
        mol (.getAtomContainer parse)
        dg (.depict (DepictionGenerator.) mol)]
    (if warning
      (println warning)
      (do
        (.writeTo dg "inchi.svg")
        (println "Success")))))

(use-inchi "InChI=1S/C6H12O6/c7-1-2-3(8)4(9)5(10)6(11)12-2/h2-11H,1H2/t2-,3-,4+,5-,6+/m1/s1")
=> Success
```

Environment:
```
$ java --version
openjdk 17.0.5 2022-10-18
OpenJDK Runtime Environment (build 17.0.5+8-Debian-2)
OpenJDK 64-Bit Server VM (build 17.0.5+8-Debian-2, mixed mode, sharing)
```

* CDK 2.8 from maven
* `net.sf.jni-inchi` 0.8 from maven

```

Marvin JS:
https://marvinjs-demo.chemaxon.com/latest/

```
alpha-D-glucose: InChI=1S/C6H12O6/c7-1-2-3(8)4(9)5(10)6(11)12-2/h2-11H,1H2/t2-,3-,4+,5-,6+/m1/s1
alpha-L-glucose: InChI=1S/C6H12O6/c7-1-2-3(8)4(9)5(10)6(11)12-2/h2-11H,1H2/t2-,3-,4+,5-,6+/m0/s1
```

OPSIN:
https://opsin.ch.cam.ac.uk/

```
alpha-D-glucose: InChI=1S/C6H12O6/c7-1-2-3(8)4(9)5(10)6(11)12-2/h2-11H,1H2/t2-,3-,4+,5-,6+/m1/s1
alpha-L-glucose: InChI=1S/C6H12O6/c7-1-2-3(8)4(9)5(10)6(11)12-2/h2-11H,1H2/t2-,3-,4+,5-,6+/m0/s1
```

BTW you really should not parse InChIs :-). They are an identifier not a representation for transmitting chemical data. It is an addition not the primary presentation.

Scaffold Generator offers the generation of different molecular scaffolds, scaffold trees, and scaffold networks.

comment.body:
Sorry last message got screwed up by email.

Ah you need to bootstrap it I think. 

The old javadoc could pickup run time dependency but that didn’t seem to work anymore (maybe extra module flags needed?) so you need to do the following:
- compile your code (main project)
- make cdk build utils depend on the new build
- rebuild the cdk-build-utils
- run javadoc:aggregate on the main project

Since we don’t really add many taglets it’s not normally such a pain although this is one of the reasons I would favour just in-lining the values as plain HTML.

> Personally, I consider javadocs as quite important and I struggle to validate them if I add/modify anything.

Preaching to the choir, I’m not the one you need to convince. #908

issue.title: AminoAcidCountDescriptor logs warning when instantiated
issue.body:
I'm getting the following warning every time I'm instantiating the AminoAcidCountDescriptor
class:
org.openscience.cdk.io.cml.CMLHandler WARN: Detected unknown convention: cdk:substructureList

I'm not a chemist so I cannot tell if it actually outputs the correct descriptor results, but at least it outputs some values when I send in a molecule with some amino acids. Should I be concerned with the error message, I assume there is some bug in there somewhere? Tested in both version 2.7.1 and 2.8. I'm running on a M1 chip mac in case that matters.

comment.body: To clarify, this is warning not an error. Please ignore the warning, we will try and suppress it in future.

comment.body:
It looks like it's just a skipped attribute in the CML input. @egonw is the CML wizard who will be able to confirm if there is some special semantics being missed or not. Based on what the descriptor is doing and the test cases I don't think there is anything wrong.

https://github.com/cdk/cdk/blob/main/storage/pdb/src/main/resources/org/openscience/cdk/templates/data/list_aminoacids.cml#L2

```xml
<list title="List of amino acids" convention="cdk:substructureList"
        xmlns="http://www.xml-cml.org/schema"
        xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
    
```

The web API (I have not idea what api you are using) expects a SMARTS and not a SMILES. There is a subtle difference but you’ve queried for a nitrogen with a hydrogen attached but there are none.

“c1ncnc1”
Or
“c1nc[nX3]c1”

Oh grrr... not finished yet but can see it still didn't pickup the SonarCloud token. This is infuriating, we could just expose the token publicly but I thought how I had set this up was a good option. i.e. me/egon need to click run on the PR
Could you rebase on master @uli-f, I think have configure SonarCloud so we can run it now.

comment.body:
Overall looks good but I want to kick the tyres on it a bit. 

Some minor comments as I've looked closer (I can't remember which parts I wrote but fully open to change my mind on good ways of doing things).

- Anyways, love it or hate it, you can store reactions are molecules (and convert back and forth) so *technically* you could iterate over molecules. But you probably want to keep it as IReaction as you have properties on the molecule IIRC (e.g. titles)?
- As noted in Egon's review/comment chain, the error handling is always tricky, I think I now favour the OPSIN like approach where you set some status on a return type, or even better on the thing you pass in (I can give an example).
- I think some parts like the property processing we can centralize - I think the V2000/V3000 might share/reuse the function but there is a duplicate in the SDFReader. Good opportunity to unify these.
Ah I miss-read Egon's input on the IO listener... personally I would prefer a return status on the record. So then the you force the user to decide what to do with them.

comment.body:
It's been on my list to rewrite the V3000 IO at some point, or rather V2000+V3000 since currently you need to know if you ``.mol`` input is V2000/V3000 before you parse it, which isn't ideal. In general the V3000 reader is not very robust and supports only a subset (bare minimum) of the format, I've added bits over the years but ultimately it needs a rewrite.

In this case the V3000 currently presumes the atom indexes are sequential, indeed all programatically generated content will be sequential. However leave this open since it's a simple fix.

Sure you've tested already but Marvin rejects it:
https://marvinjs-demo.chemaxon.com/latest/

And ChemDraw:
https://chemdrawdirect.perkinelmer.cloud/js/sample/index.html

As expected BIOVIA accepts it:
```
SQL> select smiles(mol('
  Mrv2219 11302223302D          

  0  0  0     0  0            999 V3000
M  V30 BEGIN CTAB
M  V30 COUNTS 2 1 0 0 0
M  V30 BEGIN ATOM
M  V30 1 C -6.458 3.4367 0 0
M  V30 22 C -7.7917 2.6667 0 0
M  V30 END ATOM
M  V30 BEGIN BOND
M  V30 1 1 1 22
M  V30 END BOND
M  V30 END CTAB
M  END')) from dual;
CC
```

You should get a BIOVIA draw license Rich, not expensive for a single user (much cheaper than ChemDraw for example).

comment.body:
@rapodaca did you have an old build laying around, just tested on:

```
[john@sentinel:cdk]% java -version
openjdk version "18.0.2.1" 2022-08-18
OpenJDK Runtime Environment (build 18.0.2.1+1-1)
OpenJDK 64-Bit Server VM (build 18.0.2.1+1-1, mixed mode, sharing)
[john@sentinel:cdk]%
```

And no issues with a "clean install":

```
$ mvn clean install -q -o -DskipTests  113.83s user 12.62s system 175% cpu 1:12.07 total
```

I wish this was better advertised by the JDK 18/19 are sort of like public betas and you're better using the LTS Java 8/11/17. Java 17 for example runs the build in only 20s.

```
[john@sentinel:cdk]% java -version
openjdk version "17.0.1" 2021-10-19
OpenJDK Runtime Environment (build 17.0.1+12-39)
OpenJDK 64-Bit Server VM (build 17.0.1+12-39, mixed mode, sharing)

$ mvn clean install -q -o -DskipTests  58.75s user 4.15s system 296% cpu 21.218 total
```

Hi Uli,

I'll find time to look closer but some easy fixes:
 - the build if failing due a missing file it looks likey just forgot to check something in?
 - Missing copyright header/license on the java files

At some point these went out of sync with the main AtomContainer, the order.numeric() should be compared and not the ordinal() since "unset" has the largest enum in the ordinal. We also make this function null safe since it's highly likely Query molecules have unset bond order.

I then was pondering an exception for providing a query molecule to the atom type matcher, but since we have the fall-back "X" atom type I think logging a warning makes most sense. If a caller wants to avoid the warning they should check if the molecule is a query before hand.

issue.title: Cleaner InChI mass interaction/API quality of life
issue.body:
Since InChI stores mass as a delta you need to know what the base line it is a delta from. The InChI API (and by extension JNA InChI) is asymmetric in that you pass in an exact mass and get a "isotopic shift" out - the caller then needs to translate this to something sane. I think perhaps it accepts both an exact 'mass number' or a 'isotopic shift' on input so it's not quite asymmetric but I believe it always gives an 'isotopic shift' on output.

I've just fixed the issue in CDK and found the table in the INCHI-BASE directory:
https://github.com/cdk/cdk/pull/936. It would also be possible to derive the table by round-tripping in enough values.

I wonder if doing the translation in JNA InChI would be reasonable and a more usable API?

issue.title: NPE in getInChIToStructure for radioactive elements
issue.body:
The following line throws a NullPointerException for radioactive elements like Technetium-99:
https://github.com/cdk/cdk/blob/cdk-2.8/storage/inchi/src/main/java/org/openscience/cdk/inchi/InChIToStructure.java#L195

Seems like this corresponds to `getMajorIsotope` returning null.

For example:
```java
InChIGeneratorFactory.getInstance().getInChIToStructure(
    "InChI=1S/Tc/i1+1",
    DefaultChemObjectBuilder.getInstance(),
).getAtomContainer()
```

I think the desired behavior would be to either (a) translate the NPE into a more informative CDKException, or (b) if possible, avoid the NPE altogether and continue generating the atom container.

comment.body:
Here is the mass table:
https://github.com/metamolecular/inchi/blob/0fc7adc58d4ff1c481b26e0de53cc8a404c3d381/INCHI_BASE/src/util.c

(Official code is "source available" Richard has rehosted so easy to link here)

OK I'm amazed that went unnoticed for so long. Basically an obvious omission in the BFS/shortest-path finding code, or rather a specialisation of it which takes a permutation of the vertices and only gives you paths that are lexicographically descending. Some bonkers PhD student wrote this years ago (me) and I had to relearn what was going on.

issue.title: Flipped stereochemistry for Glucose using `InChiToStructure`
issue.body:
I am parsing this InChI:
```
InChI=1S/C6H12O6/c7-1-2-3(8)4(9)5(10)6(11)12-2/h2-11H,1H2/t2-,3-,4+,5-,6+/m1/s1
```
and producing an image with `DepictionGenerator`.
I expect an image like:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/26444312/202723071-93bd5376-ac04-4dd4-940a-5efc7699abf6.png)

But this is the image that CDK is generating:
![inchi](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/26444312/202723140-6bd78a6d-fa3e-4859-836b-9e2bdc93f173.svg)

Note that I am expecting [L-Glucose](https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/L-Glucose#section=2D-Structure) but the image produced is of [D-Glucose](https://pubchem.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/compound/D-Glucose).

The code I am using is essentially [this](https://github.com/ipb-halle/cdk-inchi-to-svg/blob/master/cdk-inchi-to-svg/src/main/java/de/ipb_halle/msbi/cdk_inchi_to_svg/App.java):

```clojure
(defn use-inchi [inchi]
  (let [cob (DefaultChemObjectBuilder/getInstance)
        genf (InChIGeneratorFactory/getInstance)
        parse (.getInChIToStructure genf inchi cob)
        ret (.getReturnStatus parse)
        warning (if (= ret INCHI_RET/WARNING)
                  (.getMessage parse)
                  nil)
        mol (.getAtomContainer parse)
        dg (.depict (DepictionGenerator.) mol)]
    (if warning
      (println warning)
      (do
        (.writeTo dg "inchi.svg")
        (println "Success")))))

(use-inchi "InChI=1S/C6H12O6/c7-1-2-3(8)4(9)5(10)6(11)12-2/h2-11H,1H2/t2-,3-,4+,5-,6+/m1/s1")
=> Success
```

Environment:
```
$ java --version
openjdk 17.0.5 2022-10-18
OpenJDK Runtime Environment (build 17.0.5+8-Debian-2)
OpenJDK 64-Bit Server VM (build 17.0.5+8-Debian-2, mixed mode, sharing)
```

* CDK 2.8 from maven
* `net.sf.jni-inchi` 0.8 from maven

comment.body: No time wasted, you can still it is a little bit flakey and had to make changes recently to get things to work on JDK 11/17. The rebase should (hopefully) we relatively painless.

comment.body:
Can you double check everything on HotSpot 17. There shouldn't be an issue with other versions but just tested locally an everything seems to be OK (other than the HTML warnings).

```
[john@sentinel:cdk-build-util]% java -version
openjdk version "17.0.1" 2021-10-19
OpenJDK Runtime Environment (build 17.0.1+12-39)
OpenJDK 64-Bit Server VM (build 17.0.1+12-39, mixed mode, sharing)
```

```
[john@sentinel:cdk-build-util]% git status
On branch master
Your branch is up to date with 'origin/master'.

nothing to commit, working tree clean
```

```
[john@sentinel:cdk-build-util]% mvn clean install -q
```

```
[john@sentinel:cdk-build-util]% cd ../cdk
[john@sentinel:cdk]% mvn javadoc:aggregate -q
```

```
8 errors
100 warnings
```

But the doc should be fine:

```

target/site/apidocs/index.html
```

This molecule is a little broken (some of the carbons are missing a double bond) but that should cause a problem. Indeed if we pass the molecule directly into the Cycles API all is fine. It's some complex interaction with how the aromaticity creates subgraphs/subsets.

issue.title: Scaffold Generator integration into CDK
issue.body:
Integrates the Scaffold Generator functionalities (described [here](https://doi.org/10.26434/chemrxiv-2022-7tf0h)) into the new CDK "scaffold" package. 
Scaffold Generator offers the generation of different molecular scaffolds, scaffold trees, and scaffold networks.

comment.body:
tools/scaffold then maybe a new module in app(s)/ I can’t remember what I called it but high level/convenient depict is done a bit a like this. 

Anyways all looks fine I just think it’s useful to make the coupling as loose as possible. When a lot of new dependencies are added to a module/pom it’s normally a sign it’s doing to much. 

Unless it’s designed in from the start it can be tricky to tease out the API from an end-to-end tool

issue.title: AminoAcidCountDescriptor logs warning when instantiated
issue.body:
I'm getting the following warning every time I'm instantiating the AminoAcidCountDescriptor
class:
org.openscience.cdk.io.cml.CMLHandler WARN: Detected unknown convention: cdk:substructureList

I'm not a chemist so I cannot tell if it actually outputs the correct descriptor results, but at least it outputs some values when I send in a molecule with some amino acids. Should I be concerned with the error message, I assume there is some bug in there somewhere? Tested in both version 2.7.1 and 2.8. I'm running on a M1 chip mac in case that matters.

comment.body: @egonw Pretty sure just removing the ignored ``convention="cdk:substructureList"`` would be fine?

comment.body:
Sorry last message got screwed up by email.

Ah you need to bootstrap it I think. 

The old javadoc could pickup run time dependency but that didn’t seem to work anymore (maybe extra module flags needed?) so you need to do the following:
- compile your code (main project)
- make cdk build utils depend on the new build
- rebuild the cdk-build-utils
- run javadoc:aggregate on the main project

Since we don’t really add many taglets it’s not normally such a pain although this is one of the reasons I would favour just in-lining the values as plain HTML.

> Personally, I consider javadocs as quite important and I struggle to validate them if I add/modify anything.

Preaching to the choir, I’m not the one you need to convince. #908

issue.title: AminoAcidCountDescriptor logs warning when instantiated
issue.body:
I'm getting the following warning every time I'm instantiating the AminoAcidCountDescriptor
class:
org.openscience.cdk.io.cml.CMLHandler WARN: Detected unknown convention: cdk:substructureList

I'm not a chemist so I cannot tell if it actually outputs the correct descriptor results, but at least it outputs some values when I send in a molecule with some amino acids. Should I be concerned with the error message, I assume there is some bug in there somewhere? Tested in both version 2.7.1 and 2.8. I'm running on a M1 chip mac in case that matters.

comment.body: To clarify, this is warning not an error. Please ignore the warning, we will try and suppress it in future.

comment.body:
It looks like it's just a skipped attribute in the CML input. @egonw is the CML wizard who will be able to confirm if there is some special semantics being missed or not. Based on what the descriptor is doing and the test cases I don't think there is anything wrong.

https://github.com/cdk/cdk/blob/main/storage/pdb/src/main/resources/org/openscience/cdk/templates/data/list_aminoacids.cml#L2

```xml
<list title="List of amino acids" convention="cdk:substructureList"
        xmlns="http://www.xml-cml.org/schema"
        xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance"
    
```

comment.body:
How are you accessing this? I don’t provide any of those API points.

Mainly curious.

The web API (I have not idea what api you are using) expects a SMARTS and not a SMILES. There is a subtle difference but you’ve queried for a nitrogen with a hydrogen attached but there are none.

“c1ncnc1”
Or
“c1nc[nX3]c1”
